node.text:
Dorchester is where I bought my first home, put down roots, grew my family & launched my first City Council campaign. For a decade plus I was so very proud to call Dorchester my home. The sense of community & tradition, the political & civic engagement, the diversity, the restaurants, the arts, the @DorchesterReporter, local sports leagues & of course the parade organized each year as a labor of love by so many dedicated volunteers. 

The Dot Day parade may have been cancelled this year but we were out in full force. 

Kicked off the week cheering on the Ravens. Spent the day filling up on good food and vaccinated hugs with neighbors. Ended the day in true Dorchester fashion with house parties.

Happy Dorchester Day 💛

node.text:
Malcolm X. el-Hajj Malik el-Shabazz. Truth teller. Justice seeker. Freedom fighter.

Father. Husband. Son of Roxbury. 

Today is his 96th birthday.

Before his assassination in 1965, he spent some early, formative years in Boston.

In 2017 when I was on the City Council, I worked with @wutrain and @titojacksonboston to get the city to formally recognize #MalcolmXDay.

Today, I support the Shabazz family’s calls to fully reopen the investigation into his assassination. 

If you’re looking for a way to celebrate his life and legacy, pick up The Autobiography of Malcolm X. 

My father gave me a copy when I was a kid.
